			"components": [
				{
					"role": "title",
					"layout": "titleLayout",
					"text": "How to Make the Most Popular Drink at the US Open",
					"textStyle": "titleStyle"
				},
				{
					"role": "intro",
					"layout": "introLayout",
					"text": "The Grey Goose and Chamboard-filled Honey Deuce has been the event's trademark drink for nine years running.",
					"textStyle": "introStyle",
					"format": "markdown"
				},
				{
					"role": "divider",
					"stroke": {
						"color": "#FFF0"
					},
					"layout": "blackStrokeLayout1",
					"style": "baseStrokeStyle"
				},
				{
					"role": "author",
					"layout": "authorLayout",
					"text": "By Sam Dangremond",
					"textStyle": "authorStyle"
				},
				{
					"role": "divider",
					"stroke": {
						"color": "#FFF0"
					},
					"layout": "blackStrokeLayout2",
					"style": "baseStrokeStyle"
				},
				{
					"role": "body",
					"text": "The Kentucky Derby has the [mint julep](http://google.com). The US Open has the Honey Deuce. Created by Grey Goose mixologist Nick Mautone in 2007, the tasty combination of vodka, lemonade, and raspberry liqueur has become the signature beverage of the tennis tournament.",
					"layout": "bodyLayout",
					"textStyle": "bodyStyleFirst",
					"format": "markdown"
				},
				{
					"role": "body",
					"text": "The best part? The frozen honeydew melon balls used a garnish. Resembling tennis balls, they remind imbibers what the US Open is really about (not that the drinks and food at the USTA Billie Jean King National Tennis Center aren't great on their own).",
					"layout": "bodyLayout",
					"textStyle": "bodyStyle",
					"format": "markdown"
				},
				{
					"role": "divider",
					"stroke": {
						"color": "#FFF0"
					},
					"layout": "blackStrokeLayout3",
					"style": "baseStrokeStyle"
				},
				{
					"role": "pullquote",
					"layout": "pullQuoteLayout",
					"text": "\u201CMautone, Grey Goose says, decided to combine the vodka with lemonade to quench spectators' thirst in the late summer heat\u201D",
					"textStyle": "pullQuoteStyle",
					"format": "markdown"
				},
				{
					"role": "divider",
					"stroke": {
						"color": "#FFF0"
					},
					"layout": "blackStrokeLayout4",
					"style": "baseStrokeStyle"
				},
				{
					"role": "body",
					"text": "Mautone, Grey Goose says, decided to combine the vodka with lemonade to quench spectators' thirst in the late summer heat. The Chambord adds a raspberry kick. In addition, since honeydew melons are at their peak in summer months, the melon balls are an appropriate finishing touch.",
					"layout": "bodyLayout",
					"textStyle": "bodyStyle",
					"format": "markdown"
				},
				{
					"role": "body",
					"text": "More than 150,000 Honey Deuces have been sold since its inception. Here's how to make the drink at home.",
					"layout": "bodyLayout",
					"textStyle": "bodyStyle",
					"format": "markdown"
				},
				{
					"role": "heading1",
					"layout": "heading1Layout",
					"text": "Ingredients",
					"textStyle": "heading1Style",
					"format": "markdown"
				},
				{
					"role": "body",
					"text": "\n* 1.25 parts Grey Goose vodka\n* Fresh squeezed lemonade\n * .5 part Chambord or premium raspberry liqueur\n* Crushed ice\n* Honeydew melons for garnish",
					"layout": "bodyLayout",
					"textStyle": "bodyStyle",
					"format": "markdown"
				},
				{
					"role": "heading1",
					"layout": "heading1Layout",
					"text": "Instructions",
					"textStyle": "heading1Style",
					"format": "markdown"
				},
				{
					"role": "body",
					"text": "\n1. Fill a chilled highball glass with crushed ice and add Grey Goose vodka.\n2. Top with lemonade to just below the rim and then add Chambord.\n3. Garnish with honeydew melon balls.",
					"layout": "bodyLayout",
					"textStyle": "bodyStyle",
					"format": "markdown"
				},
				{
					"role": "body",
					"text": "Besides the cash and the hooch, the safe also contained\u2014and this is where it gets interesting\u2014a book called _A Guide for the Perplexed_, published in 1977, that appears to contain clues. Inside, there was a black and white photo of a mystery (and, might we add, dapper) man.",
					"layout": "bodyLayout",
					"textStyle": "bodyStyle",
					"format": "markdown"
				},
				{
					"role": "banner_advertisement",
					"bannerType": "standard"
				}
			]
		}
